[Student "S"]
{Wow. You can tell that this is going to be tough to bid scientifically. You decide to start with a transfer bid, 2\H. Partner replies 2\S.  

Wow. You can tell that this is going to be tough to bid scientifically. You decide to start with a transfer bid, 2\H. Partner replies 2\S. 

You know there are enough points for slam, but not enough for a Grand Slam. Asking for Aces will get you nowhere because if partner shows only one Ace you will still think you should be in slam. So you take a shot and bid 6\S.(If you don't think you would really do this, I won't hold it against you.)

The contract would be 6\S played by South.

North plays 6\S. East leads the \HK. Of course you take your \HA.

Loser List: \S = 0 : \H = 0 : \D = 2 : \C = 0 :: Total = 2The Losers are counted from dummy's long-trump hand for simplicity.

The \C suit must be established to take one of the \D losers. But there may be an entry problem since the opening lead has taken out one of your entries already.

Pull trumps in two rounds, (you got a break there), leaving the \SK in your hand as an entry. 

If you now play \CA, \CK, and then ruff a \C you will succeed when the \Cs split 3-3. But if they are 4-2, then you will fail because you only have the one entry to your hand. 

A better plan is to play a small \C from each hand. This gives the defense a \C trick but you can win their return, play a \C to the \C A, take the \CK, then ruff the <b>FOURTH</b> \C. This will establish the <b>FIFTH</b> \C and you still have the \SK for an entry.

This is a really good idea to keep in mind when you have a doubleton opposite A K x x x.

If you can afford to lose a trick in the suit you can make do with one fewer entry just by ducking the first round. Basically it gives you three plays in the suit before you take your ruff. 

But what if the contract had been 7\S?

Obviously you couldn't afford to lose a trick so you would have to bang down the two top \Cs, then ruff one and hope the suit was splitting 3-3.}
[Play "W"]HK

